age of urethra, vagina, and anal canal","Allows passage of sacral nerve roots","Enables passage of piriformis muscle"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elevator hiatus\u003C/strong\u003E is a diamond-shaped opening in the pelvic floor formed by the medial borders of the levator ani muscles. It allows passage of the urethra, vagina (in women), and anal canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator canal\u003C/strong\u003E is a separate opening in the lateral pelvic wall that transmits the obturator vessels and nerve. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epiriformis muscle\u003C/strong\u003E originates from the anterior surface of the sacrum and exits through the greater sciatic foramen. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epudendal vessels and nerve\u003C/strong\u003E pass through the greater and lesser sciatic foramina. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esacral nerve roots\u003C/strong\u003E exit through the anterior sacral foramina.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The levator hiatus is an opening in the pelvic floor through which the urethra, vagina (in women), and anal canal pass.","The levator hiatus is formed by the medial borders of the levator ani muscles."],"references":["Cheng LK, O\u0027Grady G, Du P, Egbuji JU, Windsor JA, Pullan AJ. Gastrointestinal system. Wiley Interdiscip Rev Syst Biol Med. 2010 Jan-Feb;2(1):65-79. doi: 10.1002/wsbm.19. PMID: 20836011; PMCID: PMC4221587","Kahai P, Mandiga P, Wehrle CJ, Lobo S. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Large Intestine. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing, Treasure Island (FL); 2023. PMID: 29261962","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47628"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15665"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type